A weather research group stores daily temperature readings as a 2D int array, where each row represents one weather station's readings for several days. The group wants to filter out stations whose total weekly temperature does not exceed a given threshold.

public class GridUtils {
    /** Returns a new 2D int array containing only those rows of grid whose sum of
     *  elements is strictly greater than threshold. The returned array's rows must
     *  appear in the same relative order as in grid, and each returned row must be
     *  a copy of the original row (same length, same values). The parameter grid
     *  must NOT be modified. You may assume grid is non-null, has at least one row,
     *  and every row has the same length (>= 1). */
    public static int[][] filterRows(int[][] grid, int threshold) { /* implement */ }
}

Write the static method filterRows as described in the comment.

reference_solution:
public class GridUtils {
    public static int[][] filterRows(int[][] grid, int threshold) {
        int count = 0;
        for (int r = 0; r < grid.length; r++) {
            int sum = 0;
            for (int c = 0; c < grid[r].length; c++) {
                sum += grid[r][c];
            }
            if (sum > threshold) {
                count++;
            }
        }

        int[][] result = new int[count][];
        int idx = 0;
        for (int r = 0; r < grid.length; r++) {
            int sum = 0;
            for (int c = 0; c < grid[r].length; c++) {
                sum += grid[r][c];
            }
            if (sum > threshold) {
                int[] copy = new int[grid[r].length];
                for (int c = 0; c < grid[r].length; c++) {
                    copy[c] = grid[r][c];
                }
                result[idx] = copy;
                idx++;
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
}

